Vanasse Hangen Brustlin, Inc. (VHB) has evaluated the traffic impacts associated
with the proposed resort-style seasonal cottage development located on Seabrook
Road in Salisbury, Massachusetts. The site is generally bounded by Seabrook Road
to the west, marshland to the east, Forest Road to the south, and the
Salisbury/Seabrook town line to the north.
Under existing conditions the site is approximately 94 acres. The proposed project
involves the construction of approximately 270 seasonal cottages on the site along
with associated amenities including pool areas, a pavilion, a clubhouse, and a gym.
Primary access to the site is proposed via a single unsignalized driveway on
Seabrook Road just south of the town line. Emergency access is also proposed
through a gated driveway connecting to Forest Road.

The proposed project is expected to generate approximately 854 new vehicle trips on
an average weekday with 81 new vehicle trips during the weekday morning peak
hour and 84 new vehicle trips during the weekday evening peak hour. On a
Saturday, the project is expected to generate approximately 830 new vehicle trips,
with 97 new vehicle trips during the Saturday midday peak hour.
Capacity analyses were conducted for each of the study area intersections under 2010
Existing conditions, 2015 No-Build conditions (without the proposed
redevelopment), and 2015 Build conditions (with the proposed redevelopment).
Based on the results of the capacity analysis, the study area intersections are expected
to operate at good levels of service (LOS B or better) with substantial reserve capacity
during the peak periods under 2015 Build conditions.
To enhance safety measures along Seabrook Road, VHB recommends the
implementation of improvements along Seabrook Road consisting of replacing the
pavement markings, upgrading the signage, and the construction of a new shoulder
along both sides of the roadway. The pavement markings should consist of the
installation of a new double-yellow centerline and single-white edge lines along
Seabrook Road. Additional speed limit and warning signs should be installed where
needed. To supplement the speed limit signs, solar-powered speed radar signs
should also be installed at both endpoints of the roadway improvement project.
MassDOT has completed final design review of a project involving traffic signal
upgrades at four intersections in the area, one of which is the intersection of
Lafayette Road (Route 1) at Route 286. The work involves the installation of new
traffic signal equipment (conduit, wiring, signal posts, detectors, signs/pavement
markings, pre-emption equipment) and minor grading and drainage improvements.
While the project is scheduled to be advertised for bid in October 2010, there is
currently no funding available for construction of the improvements. VHB
recommends that the Proponent work with the Town of Salisbury to determine if
there is an opportunity to participate with the implementation of this project.
VHB also recommends that the Proponent provide a shuttle bus that will transport
residents and visitors of the development to the beach areas to the east of the site.
Due to the seasonal nature of the development and the likelihood that the residents
and visitors will access the beach areas while at the development, this shuttle bus is
expected to reduce the amount of beach-related vehicular traffic along the roadways
in the vicinity of the project site.
This traffic study finds that the existing transportation infrastructure within the
study area, upgraded with the proposed improvement measures, will accommodate
the traffic volumes projected to be generated by the project.
This traffic study documents the findings of the traffic evaluation conducted for the
project including an assessment of existing conditions, projection of future traffic
volumes without and with the proposed development, analysis of impacts of the
proposed development and recommendations for improving existing capacity
deficiencies as well as to offset project related traffic impacts.

The proposed project involves the construction of approximately 270 seasonal

unsignalized driveway on Seabrook Road just south of the town line. Emergency

This traffic assessment has been conducted in three stages. The first stage involved
an assessment of existing traffic conditions within the project area including an
inventory of existing roadway geometry; observations of traffic flow, including daily
and peak period traffic counts; and a review of vehicular crash data.
The second stage of the study established the framework for evaluating the
transportation impacts of the proposed project. Specific travel demand forecasts for
the project were assessed along with future traffic demands on the study area
roadways due to projected background traffic growth and other proposed area
development that will occur, independent of the proposed development. The year
2015, a five-year time horizon, was selected as the design year for analysis for the
preparation of this traffic impact and access assessment to satisfy the Executive Office
of Environmental Affairs/Executive Office of Transportation [EOEEA/EOT] guidelines.
The third and final stage involved conducting traffic analyses to identify both
existing and projected future roadway capacities and demands. This analysis was
used as the basis for determining potential project impacts and potential mitigation
Evaluation of the transportation impacts associated with the proposed project requires a
thorough understanding of the existing transportation system in the project study area.
Existing transportation conditions in the study area include roadway geometry, traffic
controls, daily and peak period traffic flow, and vehicular crash information data. Each
of these elements is described in detail below.

Pike Street intersects Lafayette Road from the east and west to form a four-legged,
signalized intersection under MassDOT jurisdiction. The Pike Street east and westbound

Pedestrian facilities are not provided at the intersection. The traffic signal operates in
three phases, with an advance phase provided for the Lafayette Road southbound
approach. During field observations conducted as part of this study, the traffic signal
was not operating under actuated control, although vehicle detectors are present along

the intersection reach their maximum, regardless if there are any vehicles on the
approach. The lack of actuation at the traffic signal provided excessive green time for the
Pike Street approaches and resulted in lengthy delays and queuing along Lafayette Road.
The Massachusetts Department of Transportation (MassDOT) is currently in the process

The evaluation criteria used to analyze area intersections in this traffic study are

[LOS] is used to denote the different operating conditions that occur on a given
roadway segment under various traffic volume loads. It is a qualitative measure that
considers a number of factors including roadway geometry, speed, travel delay, and
Level of service provides an index to the operational qualities of a roadway
segment or an intersection. Level-of-service designations range from A to F, with
LOS A representing the best operating conditions and LOS F representing the
worst operating conditions. Level-of-service is derived directly from the delay
Delay is a complex measure that depends upon a number of variables such as
quality of signal progression, cycle length, allocation of green time, and volume-
to-capacity (v/c) ratio. Of all the factors cited, v/c ratios have the least effect on
delay. Thus, for any given v/c ratio, a range of delay values [and, therefore,
levels of service] may result. Conversely, for a given level of service, the v/c
ratio may lie anywhere within a broad range. Comparison of intersection
capacity results therefore requires that in addition to the LOS, the other measures
of effectiveness [MOEs] must also be considered.
Transportation Research Board, Highway Capacity Manual, Washington, D.C., 2000.
The level-of-service designations, which are based on delay, are reported differently
for signalized and unsignalized intersections. For signalized intersections, the
analysis considers the operation of all traffic entering the intersection and the
LOS designation is for overall conditions at the intersection. For unsignalized
intersections, the analysis assumes that traffic on the mainline is not affected by
traffic on the side streets. Thus, the LOS designation is for the critical movement
exiting the side street, and is typically the left turn out of the side street or site

VHB conducted a sight distance evaluation for the intersection of Seabrook Road and
the proposed Site Driveway. Measurements were taken for Stopping Sight Distance
and Intersections Sight Distance at this intersection in accordance with guidelines
provided by the American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials
Sight distance considerations are divided into two categories: Stopping Sight
Distance (SSD) and Intersection Sight Distance (ISD). Stopping sight distance (SSD)
is the distance required for a vehicle approaching an intersection from either
direction to perceive, react and come to a complete stop to avoid colliding with an
object in the road. In this respect, SSD can be considered as the minimum visibility
criterion for the safe operation of an unsignalized intersection.
Intersection sight distance (ISD) is based on the time required for perception, reaction
and completion of the desired critical exiting maneuver (typically, a left turn) once
the driver on a minor street approach (or a driveway) decides to execute the
maneuver. Calculations for ISD include the time to (1) turn left and clear the near
half of the intersection without conflicting with the vehicles approaching from the
left; and (2) upon turning left, to accelerate to the operating speed on the roadway
without causing approaching vehicles on the main road to unduly reduce their
speed. In this context, ISD can be considered as a desirable visibility criterion for the
safe operation of an unsignalized intersection. The AASHTO sight distance criteria
are contained in the Appendix of this document. Table 8 presents a summary of the
ISD and SSD analysis, based on the observed 85th percentile speed of 33 mph along
Seabrook Road as provided by Cottage Advisors, LLC. The speed data is provided

The primary goal of implementing a transportation demand management (TDM)
plan for any given development is to reduce the overall traffic impacts of the project
by minimizing the reliance on single-occupancy vehicles as the primary travel mode.
While TDM options are limited for residential developments, the proposed project
has a unique opportunity because of its location and the nature of a significant
portion of its vehicle trips. Given the project’s location and the fact that a significant
portion of the recreational vehicle trips that will travel off site are destined for the
beach, the implementation of a shuttle bus would result in a decrease in the number
of vehicle trips traveling off site. VHB recommends that the Proponent provide a
shuttle bus that will transport residents and visitors of the development to the beach
areas to the east of the site. The anticipated route for this shuttle would be to travel
north on Seabrook Road to South Main Street, east to Route 286, and east to Route 1A
to various destinations. Due to the seasonal nature of the development and the
likelihood that the residents and visitors will access the beach areas while at the
development, this shuttle bus is expected to reduce the amount of beach-related
vehicular traffic along the roadways in the vicinity of the project site.
This traffic study presented a detailed traffic assessment to evaluate the impacts
associated with the construction of 270 recreational homes to be located off Seabrook
Road in the Town of Salisbury near the New Hampshire State Line. The project site
is approximately 94 acres in size with access planned via an unsignalized driveway
that intersects the east side of Seabrook Road. In addition, gated emergency access is
proposed off of Forest Road. The proposed project is expected to generate
approximately 854 new vehicle trips on an average weekday with 81 new vehicle
trips during the weekday morning peak hour and 84 new vehicle trips during the
weekday evening peak hour. On a Saturday, the project is expected to generate
approximately 830 new vehicle trips, with 97 new vehicle trips during the Saturday
Detailed traffic analyses indicate that the project is not expected to have a significant
impact upon study area roadways and intersections. The study area intersections are
expected to operate at good levels of service (LOS B or better) with substantial
reserve capacity under the 2015 Build conditions.
To enhance safety measures along Seabrook Road, VHB recommends the
implementation of improvements along Seabrook Road consisting of replacing the
pavement markings, upgrading the signage, and the construction of a new shoulder
along both sides of the roadway. The pavement markings should consist of the
installation of a new double-yellow centerline and single-white edge lines along
Seabrook Road. Additional speed limit and warning signs should be installed where
needed. To supplement the speed limit signs, solar-powered speed radar signs
should also be installed at both endpoints of the roadway improvement project.
VHB recommends that the Proponent work with the Town of Salisbury to determine
if there is an opportunity to participate with the implementation of the MassDOT
signal improvements at the intersection of Lafayette Road and Route 286.
VHB also recommends that the Proponent provide a shuttle bus that will transport
residents and visitors of the development to the beach areas to the east of the site.
Due to the seasonal nature of the development and the likelihood that the residents
and visitors will access the beach areas while at the development, this shuttle bus is
expected to reduce the amount of beach-related vehicular traffic along the roadways
in the vicinity of the project site.
This traffic study finds that the existing transportation infrastructure within the
study area, upgraded with the proposed improvement measures, will accommodate
the traffic volumes projected to be generated by the project.
